column64: [Complainant establishing Legitimate Interest]note that although the mark was unregistered in both SG and Australia, it was held that legitimate interest can still be established as per the tort of passing off + it can be considered a well-known mark. [Bad Faith - Other Grounds]A further observation may also be made that the Respondent changed the name of the homyoga.sg website to _homy oga” and then subsequently to _home yoga”, such that phonetically the website still substantially sounds the same as the Complainantês mark _HOM YOGA”, notwithstanding the difference in writing. These matters do not sit well with the bona fide use of the domain name under the third requirement.

column58: (Phone-N-Phone Service (Bermuda) Ltd v Schlomi (Salomon) Levi) (WIPO Case No. D2000-0040)
column64: Respondent and Complainant had a business relationship, where Respondent was supposed to help the Complainant register the domain name, but breached the trust by registering it under the Respondent's name instead of Complainant's name and offering to sell for $7K

the Complainant also has 2 international registrations for the "LELO" trademark under the Madrid system administered by WIPO: one under International Class 3 + International Class 10 and another one under International Class 24 + International Class 25Complainant did not discharge burden of proof of goodwill because did not provide details of sales in singapore Panel also put on record that the Respondent was opportunisitc in registering the DOmain names but this itself does not provide grounds to transfer the domain names to Complainant

column64: Court saw registering a trademark after the agreement to use the domain name / trade mark expired as lacking legitimate interest + bad faithOther indication of bad faith was that the respondent operated via other names e.g. Cambridge Information Technology etc, and there was no need to use linguaphone.

column64: The Complainant claims that the Respondentês name _This domain for sale” and registered and mailing addresses _buyname@msn.com” are self-evident of Respondentês intention to convey to the public that the Domain Name is for sale. However given the actual use of the Domain Name by the Respondent, this Panel is not prepared to rely only on such evidence to conclude that the Respondent registered the Domain Name solely for the purpose of selling it, and is not prepared to make a finding of bad faith of this premise alone. the Panel finds it noteworthy that not only has the Respondent failed to file any Response, but has also indicated to the Provider that he has no intention to do so. The Panel does infer that the evidence failed to be filed by the Respondent would not- 15 -have been favourable to the Respondent, so his conduct in default of the Rule is additional illustration of bad faith on his part.

column64: "administrative panel does not find evidence of foreign trade mark applications or these blanket statements from other panels to be conclusive that MTV is a famous or well-known mark. MTV must show they have exclusive rights over "MTV" per se. and the decisions of other jurisdictions have no bearing on Singapore.Disclaimed their exclusive rights over Music and Television and Music Televisisoon and separately the letters M and TVPanel found at best weak legal rights over MTV, but no real exclusive rights. Doubts over whether would succeed in passing offfound that on its own, offer to sell domain name for USD$200,000 cannot establish that domain name was registered or acquired primarily for the purpose of selling it to Complainant
